******
[5] Spain: details
Date: Mon 22 Aug 2022
Source: Diario Sur, Europa Press report [in Spanish, trans., abridged, edited]
https://www.diariosur.es/sociedad/salud/espana-supera-6000-casos-viruela-mono-20220822131134-nt.html


Spain has reached 6119 [now 6284] confirmed cases of monkeypox, 327 more than last Tuesday [16 Aug 2022], according to data as of 19 Aug 2022 by the National Epidemiological Surveillance Network (RENAVE), coordinated by the Ministry of Health.

By autonomous community, Madrid leads the list with 2216 cases, ahead of Catalonia (1825). The rest of the autonomous communities with less than 1000 reported cases are Andalusia (739), Valencian Community (405), Basque Country (188), Balearic Islands (169), and Canary Islands (144).

With less than 100 cases are Galicia (95), Aragon (61), Castile and Leon (57), Asturias (55), Castile-La Mancha (44), Murcia (42), Extremadura (30), Cantabria (29), Navarra (16), La Rioja (4), Ceuta (0) and Melilla (0).

Of the reported cases, a total of 6009 are men and 110 are women. The ages range from 10 months to 88 years, with a median age of 37 years. Of the 5768 cases for which information is available, the 1st reported case showed symptoms on 26 Apr 2022 and the last one on 16 Aug 2022. Up to 4585 out of the 6119 cases for which information is available were men who have sex with men (75%).

The Health Department explains that there is a delay between the date of onset of symptoms and the date of diagnostic confirmation, with a median of 6 days, as well as a delay in the notification of cases, so "the interpretation of the last days of the epidemic curve must be done with caution."

Cases with clinical information presented mainly anogenital rash (59%), fever (54.4%), rash in other locations (not anogenital or oral-oral) (52.1%), and lymphadenopathies (50.8%). A total of 286 cases of the 4406 with information (6.5%) presented complications throughout their clinical process. The most common were mouth ulcers and secondary bacterial infections.

Of the 5463 cases with available information, 178 cases have required hospitalization (3.3%), with 2 deaths due to meningoencephalitis, according to the latest report from the Ministry of Health.

In 77.3 percent of the 3753 cases for which information is available, transmission was through close contact in the context of sexual intercourse and in 9.6 percent through close non-sexual contact.

Regarding attendance at mass events, of the 4571 cases with information on this variable, 786 attended an event on the dates before the onset of symptoms.

